Using the quotient‐rule for limits (since \(\lim_{x\to c}g(x)=5\neq0\)),  
\[
\lim_{x\to c}\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}
=\frac{\lim_{x\to c}f(x)}{\lim_{x\to c}g(x)}
=\frac{-3}{5}\,. 
\]

First write out the difference‐quotient and combine over a common denominator:

\[
\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}
=\frac{\frac1{x+1+h}-\frac1{x+1}}{h}
=\frac{\;\frac{(x+1)-(x+1+h)}{(x+1+h)(x+1)}\;}{h}
=\frac{-h}{(x+1+h)(x+1)}\cdot\frac1h
=-\frac1{(x+1+h)(x+1)}\,. 
\] 

So the average rate of change is 
\[
\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}
=-\frac1{(x+1)(x+1+h)}\,. 
\]
